\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 With your '100 people in a room with 100 paintings' argument, you've redefined subjective to mean "tastes cannot overlap", and then you've quite righteously knocked down that strawman. And contrary to your claim, top song lists are proof enough of subjectivity - most of these lists contain very little good music, from my perspective. I guess I just cant quite grasp the objective, timeless insight into human nature that is nestled in between the bars of "Wet Ass Pussy" by Cardi B. I do not enjoy listening to it. Many people do. I don't begrudge them one bit. We simply have wildly divergent tastes, and the source of this divergence is not our biology, which is structurally similar, but our respective cultural conditioning. Does clustering of tastes exist? Certainly. No one denies this. In this respect you are shouting at a cloud. Is this clustering rooted entirely in biology? This moves us into the nature versus nurture debate, and I suspect your views on this matter are archaic. Furthermore, there is almost no continuity between someone like Sargent and someone like Rauschenberg, who I enjoy in equal measure. Their paintings cannot be compared and contrasted with respect to line, color, edge, value, etc. You would learn almost nothing from such a study. They are doing completely different things. I would suggest researching the history of the Mona Lisa. The painting was hardly known, before it was stolen and caused a scandal. It wasn't even the most famous painting in its gallery, let alone the Louvre. Now, folk like yourself hail it as some timeless masterpiece beyond all others. It's not. Sad to say, it is indeed circumstance which elevated it to public acclaim, not unlike the "Hawk Tuah" girl, Andy Warhol, or any other grossly popular product of mass media. On that note, I would also suggest taking a few Advertising/Marketing courses, if you can get to them. Your eyes will be opened to just how malleable subjectivity actually is. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 relative \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8800\'3F arbitrary, art is judged by an eclectic of factors one of which is personal preference, when all factors are accounted for an objective judgement can be made about its quality, this is always in flux depending on who and what is looking at it or is happening around it. However certain factors are more influential than others, subjective preferences are less influential on the quality than things like proportion and values. This is why there is overlap in our responses to artwork. This means that art is influenced by the subjective but this does not make it wholly subjective as if someone\u8217\'92s opinion overrides all these other factors and certainly does not make it arbitrary. If a culture is sick and degenerate and the art responds to that, it might be well adapted to the context of the culture but the quality of the art suffers on more fundamental qualities of a healthy society, explaining why herd opinion doesn\u8217\'92t always embody this objective quality either. You would learn quite a bit from such a study of a difference in technique because you would begin to understand how context shapes an artist\u8217\'92s response to how they employ the fundamentals, each one is good in their own right because in the context of the painting they have made a certain set of stylistic choices that correctly responds to what they are creating. Sargent as a representational painter uses a variation of edges and textures depending on what is being painted whereas Rauschenberg isn\u8217\'92t limited by these representational needs and is often employing many very textural effects which have a sense of harmony because of this. One can also determine which of these different artworks from these artists are better by seeing how well adapted each is to its context, from there a relative degree of adaptation can be seen and an objective judgement be formed}
