\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It seems like you are arguing against claims no one is making. Relative \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8800\'3F arbitrary, yes, but subjective \u8800\'3F arbitrary either. No one sane argues that our tastes are arbitrary. They are effects of causes. The argument here, between subjective and objective, is what those causes are. The subjective case is simply that our tastes are bounded by our biological hardware, and specified by culture, as well as personal experience. For example, your favorite color is bounded by the information processed by your ocular nerve, while your actual choice might be adjusted by the cultural fact that blue is for boys and pink is for girls. But it used to be that the objective 'masculine' color was pink, while the objective 'feminine' color was blue. Why did it switch? Which view is 'degenerate' with respect to the objective truth? And yes, one can quantify how 'well-adapted to context' an artwork is by measuring dollars and twitter mentions. The real problem with this view is that artists, the good ones, are not looking to adapt to their context. In fact, I would almost argue that this sort of success is a red flag--the less success, the more likely it is that you are doing things that you, personally, find interesting. Because for me, art is about personal human connection; communicating things which words fail to. Some people communicate interesting things, some people do not. Everyone has their own tastes for what they deem to be interesting. I prefer my tastes to everyone else's, why wouldn't I? But it is hubristic in the extreme to say that my tastes are objectively better, or closer to an objective truth, while yours are degenerate. In this respect, you might consider reframing your argument around clarity. Because I think this is what you are trying to get at. IF we consider art to be an attempt to communicate, you are either successful in your communication, or you are not. In this sense, art is objective. But don't fall into the trap of conflating market success, or success with you in particular, with 'universal/objective success' and consequently, 'objective truth'. I remember hearing an interview with a director who made a movie that he himself hated. He thought it was trash, and all the critics did too. By every 'objective' measure of sound and form, it was a terrible movie. It was a failure, and he felt like a failure. Then one day a woman approached him, in tears, and said that his movie changed her life, even saved her life--it was her favorite movie all time. The context was that her daughter had recently died, and some aspect of the film hit her hard. If the movie had been any different, by objective measures--a line tweaked, the staging more appealing, the lighting more professional--perhaps she wouldn't have had this experience. To the director, this was the realization that he had made the movie for her, perhaps her alone, and this was a joy. This gets to the danger of focusing on 'objective measures' in art, from the artist's point of view. They can blind you to unique solutions to unique problems, even prevent you from even seeing those problems as real in the first place. This is why I stopped doing master studies, because essentially all you're doing is copying down a particular set of solutions to a particular set of problems, which are themselves a particular symptom of a particular attempt to communicate. What this does is give you a hammer that makes everything look like a nail. At that point I realized that all I was doing was impersonating Sargent and others, instead of embracing my own agency and devising my own solutions to the particular things that I, uniquely me, want to communicate. This is not to say that I don't often think of a painting like you do in some of your analysis videos--that Richard Schmid method of analysis--but there is a whole lot more to the craft than how you handle edge, line, value, color, surface, etc. }
