\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 I agree with what you observe but don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t think it makes the case for a purely psychological understanding of art, which subjective naturally connotes. Art is not entirely subjective, although it does have a subjective dimension related to individual perception and psychology. When creating a work of art, a new object is brought into existence\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 something that did not exist before. This creation must align with the ontological laws of the universe to achieve harmony and balance, which are inherent in nature. The "rules of composition" in art, for example, reflect these principles, which are rooted in natural phenomena. As a result, art is not solely a psychological phenomenon but also engages with the fundamental nature of reality. The quality of art can therefore be understood as context-dependent, with varying degrees of adaptability to its environment. The argument that no one considers art arbitrary is demonstrably false. Postmodernism, for instance, often rejects objective claims about reality, suggesting that macro-narratives are unreliable. However, this conflates relativity with arbitrariness. In the case of the movie example, the positive response from one individual illustrates that the work was well-adapted to that specific context. This demonstrates that art can possess an objective quality when contextual factors are considered, even if the quality varies depending on the context. Art is not simply a form of communication, though communication is often a byproduct. It is more accurately described as the creation of a physical object that resonates with the subconscious, influenced by the ontological laws of the universe. These laws govern both the object and the psyche. This perspective aligns with the ideas of Christopher Alexander, who challenges Western paradigms by explaining why art seems wholly subjective but is instead eclectic rather than mechanistic. Cultural and temporal factors also influence art and its adaptability. While universal laws provide an objective foundation, cultural influences can create dissonance in how art is perceived. For example, popular works containing "degenerate" ideas might reflect unhealthy cultural adaptations. Even if such works are well-adapted to contemporary culture, they may fail to align with deeper universal principles, ultimately contributing to societal suffering. Studying the works of the masters is not simply a matter of imitation. Because the conditions of time and individuality differ, the process involves understanding the underlying abstractions that reflect universal laws. Applying these principles can result in art that is more harmonious and well-adapted. These abstractions form the foundation of what defines good art across different contexts but is bounds to waver depending on context. I agree there is a lot more to art than just formalism \line }}